      "writtenOn": "2020-01-29T23:52:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "VirtualHost is used only if you need to route based on Host header. This is supposedly very rare. Also I don\u0027t understand how pRPC vs HTML is relevant here. If for whatever reason you want to serve different pRPC services for different \"Host\" headers, then you\u0027d need to explicitly install prpc.Server into routers returned by VirtualHost(...). VirtualHost(...) is intentionally completely empty by default, regardless of what\u0027s installed in the default router.\n\nIf you want to serve several completely different full-featured services from several different domains, run them as several completely separate processes and don\u0027t mess with VirtualHost(...).\n\n\u003e We decided its OK not to do VirtualHost for pRPC handlers because we know they never serve HTML. But, if we add some HTML handlers there, we don\u0027t want them to accidentally go on the userContentHost.\n\nI\u0027m confused by this. Add HTML handlers where? Only handlers or pRPC services **expicitly** installed into a VirtualHost(\"user-content.host\") router would be served for \"Host: user-content.host\" requests, irregardless of what\u0027s installed in the default router. And stuff installed into the default router will be served for everything EXCEPT \"Host: user-content.host\" requests. There should be no need to ever do VirtualHost(\u003cmain host\u003e).\n\nIf this is so complicated, I\u0027m willing to delete VirtualHost and add some adhoc routing to the resultdb service directly.",
      "parentUuid": "86cccec5_4ffd0b00",
      "revId": "e4ac0c3f9a5a3369d36f742f5f1d4073511442dd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
